                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><ref target="https://www.archaeology.ie/archaeological-survey-ireland/historic-environment-viewer-application">National Monuments Service</ref> SMR ID: <idno type="SMR">WA024-061002-</idno></p> 
                                    <material type="stone">Grit</material> <!--(Macalister)-->
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                    <dimensions unit="m" source="MAC1945">
                                        <height>1.22</height>
                                        <width>0.38</width>
                                        <depth>0.15</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stone is broken in two. It was earlier in three fragments but the bottom two pieces were cemented together. The middle of the inscription on the first inscribed face is lost, as a large flake has disappeared from the top of the stone on that side (Macalister 1945, 266).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up-top-down-up-top">Inscribed on three angles (up-top-down-up-top).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription is clearly <rs type="execution" key="v-cut" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/203.html">v-cut</rs> in fine, very evenly-spaced strokes with vowel strokes just shorter versions of consonant strokes.<height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origPlace><placeName type="townland">Stradbally More (<distinct xml:lang="ga"><ref target="https://www.logainm.ie/ga/49850">An tSráidbhaile Mór </ref></distinct>)</placeName>
                                <placeName type="county">Co. Waterford</placeName>
                                <placeName type="country">Ireland</placeName>
                                <geo>52.133213, -7.449916</geo>
                            <note>ITM Coordinates: 637658, 598069</note></origPlace>
                            <origDate/>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found" when="1879">First noted by Brash, 1879. Two ogham stones, one broken (giving the impression of three stones), that were originally used as lintels over Toberkilleagh Well (WA024-061001-). Macalister has the townland name as Ballyvooney but Toberkilleagh well is clearly in the townland of Stradbally More.
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">Upright inside the small enclosure surrounding Toberkilleagh Well.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
